<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Clinton Seeks `Fast Track Authority' on Trade Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2701050694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0444 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2701050694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, January 26 (XINHUA) -- The Clinton 
Administration is looking for an extension of more flexible 
authority from congress in negotiating future trade accords, a 
top government official said here today. 
  Such authority would forbid congressional amendments when 
considering agreement ratification. The White House was given 
this authority during the global trade talks which concluded 
last month. 
  Mickey Kantor, U.S. trade representative, hinted today that 
the administration would seek the same authority when, for 
example, considering an expansion of the North America Free 
Trade Agreement (NAFTA). 
  "It is critical for negotiators for the U.S. to have fast 
track authority if we're going to reach the kind of agreements 
that congress has to ratify," Kantor said. 
  Some countries in Latin America and the Caribbean, including 
Chile and Argentina, are making efforts to join NAFTA, now the 
world's largest free trade zone in terms of territory, 
comprising the U.S., Canada, and Mexico. 
  Speaking at a hearing of the House Ways and Means Committee, 
Kantor said the administration might also seek such authority 
when negotiating bilateral investment and intellectual property 
rights treaties. 

</TEXT>

