<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shenzhen Holds Conference on Customs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2101173194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1559 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2101173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shenzhen, January 21 (XINHUA) -- Land ports in 
Shenzhen, one of the earliest opened special economic zones in 
south China's Guangdong Province, will simplify examination 
procedures to raise efficiency in the near future, a top Chinese 
official said here today. 
  Yu Xiaosong, vice-minister of the State Economic and Foreign 
Trade Commission, made the remarks at a conference held at the 
prompting of the Preparatory Committee for the Hongkong Special 
Administrative Region under the Standing Committee of the 
National People's Congress. 
  The conference put forward many constructive proposals on 
how 
to improve the management of Shenzhen port and promote the 
prosperity and stability of Hong Kong. 
  In the spirit of the conference, the land ports in Shenzhen 
will simplify the procedures for examination of incoming and 
outgoing vehicles and collect a package fee so as to improve 
efficiency. Concerned documents will be clarified for public 
supervision and work hours of ports will be extended. Upon the 
completion of the Guangzhou-Shenzhen expressway, the Huanggang 
port will experiment with around-the-clock service. 
  Lu Ping, director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office 
under the State Council and some members of the Preparatory 
Commission for the Hongkong Special Administrative Region 
attended the conference. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

